^-{ ^*BDeal of the Week 216 - October 30, 2000^*N }
^-
This week's deal is one of the rare ^*BDeals of the Week^*N that is more about bidding than card play. Whenever we focus on bidding, the e-mail feedback we receive is mixed. Some readers want to see more bidding discussion and some would prefer if we stuck with card play. Please keep the feedback coming so that we can make sure that nobody is happy all of the time!

^*BGeorge Cuppaidge^*N, of Queensland Australia, sent us this deal in which he and partner, ^*BIshmael (Ish) Del'Monte^*N, conducted a very impressive relay auction. George has been successful in Australia's major events for many years, but Ishmael (originally from New Zealand) is a relative newcomer to these ranks. Ish is still in his 20s, but he is widely considered one of the Australia's best players (as well as one of the top young players in the world).

A relay auction is characterized by one player making the cheapest bid (a relay) whenever it is his turn to bid. His partner responds to these relays by describing his hand in a very structured way. If everything goes according to plan, the relayer will eventually have enough information about his partner's hand to place the final contract with great accuracy. Relay auctions can be remarkably precise, as you will see with this week's deal.

The Australians have played a leading role in the development of relay theory. ^*BRoy Kerr^*N invented the ^*Bsymmetric relay^*N many years ago - an idea that has inspired great Australian players from ^*BDon Evans^*N in the 1960s through ^*BPaul Marston^*N, a world class player and theorist of today.
