nt|
As far as we are concerned, that is what "the great debate" in bridge should be all about - the needs of the average player. In our opinion, the game as it is now played at its highest levels is too complex for the vast majority of the world's bridge players to understand.

^*BFred Gitelman^*N, the President of ^*BBridge Base^*N, has a mother who has been playing duplicate bridge for a few years, but played socially back in the 1950s when ^*BCharles Goren^*N was successful at attracting millions of new players to the game. Goren succeeded by making bridge relatively simple for the average person to learn. In those days, even when the game was played at its highest levels, it was simple enough for the average person to understand.

That is not the case anymore. Fred's mom is bright and studious and would love to be able to talk to her son about his experiences in major tournaments. Unfortunately they are not playing the same game anymore. "Modern expert bridge" has become too complex for the average player to have any interest in following.

In our opinion, this has really hurt the game. Bridge is having trouble attracting new players and in holding the interest of those that have already learned to play. Other sports (such as tennis and golf) have been successful partly because the major championships of these sports can be shown to average players (and potential players) on television. The members of the TV audience see these games "at their best" and it all makes sense to them - they play the same games themselves! Not so with bridge. Major corporations are very interested in sponsoring the championship events of most sports. Not bridge. There are enough bridge players in the world to give these companies value for their advertising dollar, but 99% of these cannot possibly follow the game as it is played by experts today.

|
pg| ***** 8 ***** |


nt|
We do not know the answer to this problem, but we know that it is a problem. It is too late to try to put the genie back in the bottle by completely eliminating artificial bids. A line has to be drawn somewhere. The concept of "the line" may be philosophically unappealling for the lawmakers and system inventors, but, if making bridge more popular is to be a primary goal, then this line must exist (and it has to be drawn in a much different place than where it is right now).

The system makers of the world don't understand and there is a good reason for this. For the most part they are gifted players. As such, they find it close to impossible to imagine that average players could have trouble understanding their brilliant (no sarcasm intended) inventions.

If you are a regular reader of ^*BThe Deal of the Week^*N chances are that your skills place you in the top 1% of all bridge players in the world. You are likely a natural card player who has studied the game extensively and played in major tournaments for years. As such, it is very hard for you to get into the head of someone from the other 99% - the bridge players out there who do not (and cannot) understand bridge the way that you do. Have a game with your mom sometime. It will not be bridge as you know it. Show her this week's deal. She won't get it.

Our apologies to George Cuppaidge for launching this diatribe when he went to the trouble of sending us a very well bid pair of hands. The Jorj system is quite simple as relay systems go - George goes so far to call it a "natural relay system". We really do admire the accomplishments of the George Cuppaidges of the world. Our fear is that they are going to run out of people to play against before long.

